Text: Investing in Corsair Gaming, Inc. CRSR slowly becoming a disaster, what does the future for this company hold?

You reminded me there was a time, 3 yrs ago, when this sub promoted this stock and downvoted the naysayers. They IPOed at the right time, when the world was stay at home, and is just one of the many stocks that was lifted during an extraordinary point in history. The same thing is happening with DELL today, they benefitted from stay at home, and benefit from AI buildout today, but they havent done anything special. Its better to invest in companies that grow revenues by their own merit, and not by extraordinary external events.

As a long time pc gamer, this was a hard pass for me when it ipoed. The bulk of the business is components which is very competitive and low margin. Theyve made progress in peripherals but their market is niche mostly gamers and streamers. Compare that to Logitech which does peripherals for that market AND office, work from home, travel. Struck me as a decent company in a bad space. I just dont see where they can find more customers or sales to start growing again.
Sell, tax loss harvest, invest in VOO or VT

Im sorry but a company with slim to no margins and declining revenue in a competitive market will continue to lose. There is no real path for this stock to recover pc gaming isnt showing signs of picking up soon, competition like Logitech, razer and gigabyte will continue to put pressure on their margins. Also as a pc gamer I have no loyalty to third party manufacturer, I will go for the best reviewed and cheapest options most of the time. I liked my Corsair components but other companies are just as good or better. As far as their own products, they arent as good imo. If Im paying 100 for a keyboard or 50 for a mouse I wont be getting another Corsair, they were okay but should be 13 the price compared to competitors

Im sorry that you are down on it. That said, like others have noted you had a situation a few years ago where everyone was at home and that pulled forward what growth this had. Beyond that though, it makes gaming accessories theres no moat. I dont know where this gets to being cheapoverhated but in any case its just not a good business imo.

Corsair are fine but their peripherals and components are no better than anyone elses. Theyve only just done link fans which Lian li have been doing for years. Logitech tend to beat them on peripherals. They dont innovate. As an avid pc builder and fan of this sector, Id never invest in them and think theyre going to beat the SP500. Pc building is cyclical, along with COVID and WFH the 30 series and equivalent AMD gpus increased pc building fervour, but its likely going to be a few years before another wave like that, if at all given the catalysts at the time. Corsair are in every pc space near enough but dont excel in any of them. For me, Id either treat as a long term hold and DCA, or wait for an increase in market sentiment to bring them a bit higher and cut losses and treat as a lesson. Basically the whole market is down at the moment in tech so wouldnt sell at the moment.

Ok, I have to ask you. Have you played or used their equipment? I invested in Corsair in the past and I sold, but I sold because their equipment is average. Its not the best, but its not terrible. I have used their keyboards, I have a Corsair case for my pc, and I have dabbled a bit with their mice. I even used their ram for my previous pc. I even have a Corsair mouse pad that is their best product to date that I have purchased besides the ram. Nearly all their products serve their purpose but the arent known for their quality and gamers will gravitate towards more expensive or higher quality products after they become more experienced in understanding the market. Corsair products are for first time pc gamers that are trying to stay within budget but still put out a product that feels like a device for a gamer. And as you examine the peripheral market you will find...Razer, Logitech, Zowie, Glorious O and others put out a superior product. I use to not be a razer guy but their products are much higher quality but a higher price point. Though I think Logitech and Razer are beginning to recognize that budget products have a market. Point is that Corsair sort of like eating a Big Mac when one could go to Five Guys or In and Out or a Gourmet Burger place. It does the job in satisfying your appetite, but leaves a lot to be desired. Corsair has not figured out their market, they are just trying to capture all the gamers as a whole and this is why they did well financially with the gamer boom and are now struggling a bit. You should have sold two years ago because this company still has no clear plan forward.

I wouldnt invest into any company that sells gaming equipment. People are starting to wake up and figure out, that this gaming equipment is overpriced trash. My keychron k8 pro is better than every keyboard they have for half the price.
i dunno why this sub was so high on them, pc market is huge and crsr is just a small fry

In combination with levitation, this paves the way to full-scale control over the wavepacket dynamics of solid-state macroscopic quantum objects in linear and nonlinear systems."------------------------------------------------------------------"Scientists build the smallest quantum computer in the world ‚Äî it works at room temperature and you can fit it on your desk"This story from Taiwan may be closer to incorporating in a robot. Classical GPU-based data centers, like the ones used to train AI models like ChatGPT, use an unsustainable amount of energy. One large data center can use tens of megawatts of power. This power draw not only has massive implications on carbon emissions, the cost of this electricity can be millions of dollars per month. It's so large, in fact, that Microsoft is looking to bring the nuclear power plant at Three Mile Island back online, solely to power AI data centers. That's where quantum comes into play. IonQ's next generation of quantum computers, called IonQ Tempo, will be the first quantum computer to have a greater computational space than classical computers. This is because its 64 algorithmic qubits give it the ability to consider 18,446,744,073,709,551,616 different possibilities simultaneously. This is a whole order of magnitude greater than the world's most powerful supercomputer, Frontier. Frontier consumes over 60 MW of power, while Tempo is expected to consume 2-10 KW. That is 1/10,000th of the power draw, with significantly more power. Tempo is projected to be available in 2025, which will be a major inflection point for quantum computing.

As the QC industry evolves, the single metric investors should be focused on is Useable Computational States of the quantum computer. It rolls up the size and accuracy of problem a QC can solve to a commercially useful degree of accuracy. Media needs to start focusing in on that metric instead of parroting absolute garbage spin.

In general terms, Useable Computational States means the number of USEFUL qubits (n) with the computational states being 2^n.

For comparison, Ionq Forte is 2^36, Quantinuum is 2^21. and at best IBM, Google and Rigetti are 2^17. 

Experimentally, QuEra has demonstrated 2^48 with neutral atoms but could face scaling issues like the superconducting modality. IONQ‚Äôs Tempo will be 2^64 which surpasses the largest super computer in the world (Fortier).

Pull out your calculator to fully appreciate the differences in the size of problems these quantum computers can handle. LETS GET EVERYONE ON THE SAME PAGE!

PR out IonQ Achieves Industry Breakthrough ‚Äì First Trapped Ion Quantum System to Surpass 99.9% Fidelity on Barium:
Presentation from yesterday on x.  Watch and appreciate what has happened in the past 12 months.

Summary‚Ä¶ (note 3of3) pending approval.

*Neutral atoms modality has be a recent newcomer. Most notable is QuEra‚Äôs Aquila QC that has reported to have created 48 logical qubits out of 256 neutral atoms. The outstanding question is can they scale this tech with short coherence times (approx 1 second), fidelities in the 99.5% range, and a lack of true all to all connectivity. 

Feel free to copy and paste to other platforms as I welcome the vetting of this assessment. 

Remember, many major QC companies want investors to be confused, because frankly, they are losing the race.

3. Coherence Time - This is the amount of time the qubits remain in a state of entanglement with each other. The longer the coherence time the greater the ability to scale the quantum computer. Trapped ion QC‚Äôs (Ionq, Quantinuum) can maintain coherence for well over 1 minute. Other modalities are generally one second or under.

For universal quantum advantage you want high fidelity (99.9%+) two gate fidelities that have all to all connectivity with each other that maintains long coherence times. For context, IONQ‚Äôs AQ64 Tempo will be able to accurately explore a computational space that is 10.8x that of the worlds largest super computer (Frontier) on a standard household power supply.

2. Qubit Fidelity- Measures how accurately the entangled quantum state matches the ideal state (classical answer). The ideal state is a logical qubit with 99.999%+ two-gate fidelity. Both Ionq and Quantinuum have 99.9%+ fidelities (useable qubits), which at that level of accuracy, opens up almost all types of use cases. Most other modalities achieve a fidelity of at best 99.5% with most of their qubits going to error correction with no fundamental fix to their fidelity issue insight. They are facing logarithmic qubit growth to be able to scale. Ionq believes they will achieve logical qubit fidelity on their useable qubits(AQ) in 2025. Quantinuum just announce that by using error correction they created 12 logical qubits. It‚Äôs interesting, but not that useful at such a small computational space. 

2/3

Quantinuum H2 is 2^21, Ionq Forte Enterprise is 2^36 and IONQ‚Äôs soon to be announced Tempo is 2^64. Use your calculator to calculate these exponents. You will quickly find out why Ionq is the leader. I don‚Äôt mention other fidelities b/c they don‚Äôt report this metric give their challenges with error correction which severely limits their computational space. The worlds fastest super computer is Frontier. It‚Äôs top speed is 1.71 X 10^18 floating point operations per second. 

IONQ‚Äôs Tempo (AQ64) can theoretically consider a computational space equalling 18.44 X 10^18 potential solutions in parallel within approx the same timeframe.

They are different forms of compute but time to solution, or approx solution, is the key. At this point Ionq could consider a computational space 10.8X the size of Frontier. It is a fundamental inflection point where quantum computational space exceeds that of classical compute.

Frontier consumes 21MW‚Äôs of power. That is equal to the power required by 15,000 single family homes. Tempo can perform its operation on a single standard house power supply. 

Time to solution and power requirement are the two fundamental keys to quantum advantage.

I did a bit of digging and found on the CUDA-Q page that they're able to simulate up to 25 Qubits with four DGX H100 GPUs. So $40k worth of GPUs gets the same performance as IonQ Aria. Extrapolating, to get the same performance as Forte Enterprise (assuming 10 qubits increases the computational power by 2^10 or 1024), it would require about 4,000 H100 GPUs. That's near the upper limit of data center size (10-20k GPUs). Not only would this cost $40 million, which is roughly four times the price of a Forte Enterprise, it would also consume several orders of magnitude more electricity. Forte Enterprise uses, from what I can find, about 2-10 kilowatts of power. This is compared to H100s using a peak draw of 10 kilowatts EACH. So 40 megawatts for a data center that can simulate 35 qubits. 
This just goes to show how appealing IonQ's systems are. I have no doubt all five Forte Enterprises will be sold by EoY.

This paper, scan the name, is a very useful corrective on the real state of AI.  AI/LLM's are very useful, of course, for many things.  Used properly they are a great tool for productivity.  But they lack the simplest real logic and reasoning and it's not easily fixable.  Automating real human intelligence is a very hard problem.  From the paper: "The original problem formulation, of which we will present various versions in our investigation is as following: "Alice has N brothers and she also has M sisters. How many sisters does Alice‚Äôs brother have?". The problem features a fictional female person (as hinted by the "she" pronoun) called Alice, providing clear statements about her number of brothers and sisters, and asking a clear question to determine the number of sisters a brother of Alice has. The problem has a light quiz style and is arguably no challenge for most adult humans and probably to some extent even not a hard problem to solve via common sense reasoning if posed to children above certain age."  But LLM's can't do it."Alice in Wonderland: Simple Tasks Showing Complete Reasoning Breakdown in State-Of-the-Art Large Language Models"
